    45	although he would have used a uniform prior $\pi(\lambda) = 1$ in the
    46	same model $H_1$ had he been estimating $\lambda$. But then a question
    47	of principle rears up. To paraphrase Lindley's rhetorical question: Why
    48	should our prior knowledge, or ignorance, of $\lambda$ depend on the
    49	question we are asking about it? Even
    50	more puzzling: why should it depend on another parameter $\sigma$, which
    51	is itself unknown? One feels the need for a clearer rationalization.
    52	Furthermore, the difficulty was not really removed, but only concealed
    53	from view, by Jeffreys' procedure. All his stated conditions on the
    54	prior would have been met equally well had he chosen a Cauchy
    55	distribution with interquartile span $4\sigma$ instead of $\sigma$; but
    56	then all his $K$-values would have been quadrupled, leading to
    57	indifference at a very different value of the $t$-statistic \[see Eq.
    58	(5-13) below\]. We do not argue that Jeffreys made a bad choice; quite
    59	the contrary. Our point is rather that in his choice there were elements
    60	of arbitrariness, arising from a still unresolved question of principle.
    61	Pending that resolution, one is not in a position to say much about the
    62	"uniqueness" or "objectivity" of the test beyond the admitted virtue of
    63	yielding results that seem reasonable.
