   490	## Comparisons with Laplace
   491	In Bernardo's problem we have a normal sampling distribution
   492	$p(d\bar{x}|\lambda,\sigma) \sim N(\lambda,\sigma)$ with $\sigma$ known.
   493	Hypothesis $H_o$ specifies $\lambda = \lambda_o$, $H_1$ a normal prior
   494	$\pi(d\lambda|H_1) \sim N(\mu_1,\sigma_1)$, leading to a normal
   495	posterior distribution
   496	$p(d\lambda|D,H_1) \sim N(\lambda^\prime, \delta\lambda)$ where
   497	$$(δλ)^{-2} = n\sigma^{-2} + \sigma_1^{-2}$$
   498	$$\lambda^\prime = n(δλ/\sigma)^2 \bar{x} + (δλ/\sigma_1)^2 \mu_1$$
   499	
   500	Laplace,
   501	asking for the probability of a positive effect, would calculate
   502	$$P_L = p(\lambda > \lambda_o|D,H_1) = \Phi(t) \tag{5.3}$$
   503	
   504	where $\Phi(t)$ is the
   505	cumulative normal distribution, and as always,
   506	$t = (\lambda^\prime-\lambda_o)/\delta\lambda$. Bernardo (Eq. 9) finds for the
   507	posterior odds ratio
   508	$$K_B = p(H_o|D)/p(H_1|D) = \exp(-R/2)$$
