   350	
   351	From this and other case histories in which other conclusions were
   352	drawn, we can summarize the procedure of the physicist's significance
   353	test as follows: (A) Assume the alternative $H_1$, which contains a new
   354	parameter $\lambda$, true as a working hypothesis. (B) On this basis,
   355	devise an experiment which can measure $\lambda$ with the greatest
   356	possible precision. (C) Do the experiment. (D) Analyze the data as a
   357	pure estimation problem-Bayesian, orthodox, or still more informal, but
   358	in any event leading to a final "best" estimate and a statement of the
   359	accuracy claimed: $(\lambda)_{est} = \lambda^\prime \pm \delta\lambda$. It is
   360	considered good form to claim an accuracy $\delta\lambda$ corresponding
   361	to at least two, preferably three, standard deviations. (E) Let
   362	$\lambda_o$ be the correct value according to the null hypothesis $H_o$
   363	(we supposed $\lambda_o = 0$ above, but it is now best to bring it
   364	explicitly into view), and define the "statistic"
   365	
   366	$$t = (\lambda^\prime - \lambda_o)/\delta\lambda$$
   367	
   368	Then there are three possible outcomes:
